# Accessibility Rules

Apply when implementing or reviewing UI, and during Existing Project Intake when a user interface exists.

## UI Work Must Consider

- **Keyboard navigation** — all interactive flows operable without mouse
- **Semantic HTML** — correct elements (`button`, `nav`, `main`, headings hierarchy)
- **Focus states** — visible focus indicators; logical tab order
- **Contrast** — text and interactive elements meet project target (WCAG AA recommended)
- **Labels** — form inputs have associated labels; icons have accessible names
- **Readable text** — sizing, line height, zoom to 200% without loss of function
- **Responsive behavior** — usable across breakpoints documented in `STYLE_GUIDE.md`
- **Reduced motion** — respect `prefers-reduced-motion` where animations exist

See also `docs/standards/STYLE_GUIDE.md` accessibility section.

## During Existing Project Intake

When UI code exists, sample key screens/components and record:

- Missing labels or aria attributes
- Keyboard traps or missing focus management
- Color-only status indicators
- Low contrast patterns (note; do not guess exact ratios without tooling)
- Non-semantic interactive elements (`div` click handlers without roles)

Record findings in:
- `docs/project/PROJECT_HEALTH.md` — UX/accessibility domain
- `docs/project/TECH_DEBT.md` — category `ux-a11y`
- `docs/intake/INTAKE_FINDINGS.md` — if discovered during inspection

**Do not fix accessibility issues during intake** — recommend managed phases.

## Human Checkpoints

- Significant visual or UX changes may require **manual test checkpoint** and human visual approval
- Accessibility remediation affecting core flows → include manual test plan in review

## Testing

- Document a11y checks in plan test strategy (manual and/or automated tools if project uses axe, Lighthouse, etc.)
- Never claim accessibility compliance without running applicable checks or documenting gaps
